      • cookieToLogModUid

        public static final String cookieToLogModUid(String encUid)
        Convert NGINX-set user ID from cookie to log format. NGINX writes to log a hex string, but sends as cookie value a base-64 encoded something. As an example, value in the file of uid_got is Lot49Constants.TEST_MOD_UID_LOG_1 or Lot49Constants.TEST_MOD_UID_LOG_2 and value sent in a cookie field is, respectively, Lot49Constants.TEST_MOD_UID_COOKIE_1 and Lot49Constants.TEST_MOD_UID_COOKIE_2 .
        See Also:
        Module ngx_http_userid_module, http://www.lexa. ru/programs/mod-uid-eng.html, Microput, User.getCustomdata()

      • isTrue

        public static final boolean isTrue(Object o)
        Whether the specified argument can be interpreted as true. The rules as of now are the follows
        1. null is false
        2. If the object is Boolean, the answer is obvious
        3. If the object is a String, then it is lower-cased and leading/trailing whitespace is trimmed. After that, any of the following values are interpreted as false :
          1. Empty string
          2. false
          3. 0
          4. no
          5. off
          Everything else is true
        4. If the object is a Number, then a 0 value is false, everything else is true.
        5. If the object is a Collection, then an empty one is false , everything else is true.
        6. If the object is a File, the result is the same as calling File.exists().
        7. Everything else is true

      • cpmToMicro

        public static final long cpmToMicro(double cpm)
        Convert CPM value in dollars to micro-dollars per impression.

        Example: $12.45 CPM means that each impression is priced at $ $12.45/1,000=0.01245. In micro-dollars, that would be 0.01245*1,000,000=12450.

      • microToCpm

        public static final double microToCpm(long micro)
        Convert micro-dollar per impression to CPM in dollars.

        Example: 2,500 micro-dollars per-impression mean that I am willing to pay $ 2,500/1,000,000=0.0025 for each individual impression. That means that for the thousand impressions, my price (CPM) is $ 0.0025*1,000=2.5.
